snippet.textDisplay: So basically they've declared war against Free Speech. This crosses the line. Despite how much the Trump Admin and Government talk about Free Speech, our right to Free Speech is basically being taken away by a lot more companies. We are loosing America. I understand 100% that these companies, like YouTube, set their rules, and if we break them - comment removed! Your not suppose to use their service like that and I get it. YouTube was great. Fox News was great. America was getting close to great. And then... Wars on Free Speech began and wasn't challenged significantly by the government. In return, these wars escalated and went unchallenged to grow. This is how we loose our rights. Our freedom. Our voice, America. Why do you make such a big deal of protesters in Venezuela, Hong Kong, and Iran, hearing their voice but letting them get SCREWED, but you don't let Americans use 100% of their Free Speech? So, instead of long, smart, too much to handle and process comments like this, I usually resort to "We'll see what happens". Cause there is ALWAYS a consequence that you don't want, trust me, that comes with crossing the line or bad choices. I'll make more positive comments. I don't hate YouTube. I understand. I support their decision somewhat. You might be encouraging people to not use their voice in America, so when we have to, our voice will be strong, loud, and clear.

I've always felt that if you didn't like what someone else was saying, your first step is to ignore them and only make a second step if they're being confrontational because your ignoring them. I know with Carlos Maza, he got supposedly DDOSed by one of Crowder's fans so the second step is necessary in this argument. However I've always been told that you stand up against your bullies, getting authoritarian figure involved at the second step only brings about repercussions that punish all involved (which it has). Getting authoritative personal involved should be the last ditched effort since what you do on one person must be done upon yourself, it sounds unfair but you never know whom in your camp may be a bully as well and no matter if they are a righteous bully the light will be shined on them and they will burn just as much as the suspect party you wanted to burn in the first place. There is a metaphor that goes along with this jumping to get executive authority involved and that is, "This is why we can't have nice things." All these creators being "bullies" should effect you as much as the comment section which has such colorful language since this is of course the internet.
Silencing these "bullies" does nothing but excite those bullies fan bases which can result in more harmful dialogue then if you kept them on the platform; conflict only creates more conflict. I know with Steven Crowder he comes off as a dick (maybe he is one, I personally don't care) however he never advocates abuse to those whom he makes satire of and in fact encourages people of his audience to watch the more liberal/democratic/Left channels EVEN if you don't agree with them and make you crazy with how they might be factually wrong. He also mentions that if the political spectrum was on the conservative side how he'd still fight these "guide lines" just as hard because he feels that everyone should have equality with their freedom of speech and it doesn't matter whether it is on the Left or the Right, everyone should and have the voice to a different opinion.
